com.googlecode.biscotti.collect

Class SkipList<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<E>
      • java.util.AbstractList<E>
        • com.googlecode.biscotti.collect.SkipList<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E - the type of elements maintained by this list
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    SortedCollection<E>, java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable, java.lang.Iterable<E>, java.util.Collection<E>, java.util.List<E>

    public final class SkipList<E>
extends java.util.AbstractList<E>
implements java.util.List<E>, SortedCollection<E>, java.io.Serializable, java.lang.Cloneable
    A List whose elements are sorted from least to greatest according to their natural ordering, or by an explicit Comparator provided at creation. Attempting to remove or insert null elements is prohibited. Querying for null elements is allowed. Inserting non-comparable elements will result in a ClassCastException. The add(int, E) , addAll(int, Collection), and set(int, E) operations are not supported.

    The iterators obtained from the iterator() and listIterator() methods are fail-fast. Attempts to modify the elements in this list at any time after an iterator is created, in any way except through the iterator's own remove method, will result in a ConcurrentModificationException. Further, the list iterator does not support the add(E) and set(E) operations.

    This list is not thread-safe. If multiple threads modify this list concurrently it must be synchronized externally.

    Implementation Note: This implementation uses a comparator (whether or not one is explicitly provided) to perform all element comparisons. Two elements which are deemed equal by the comparator's compare(E, E) method are, from the standpoint of this list, equal.

    This class implements an array-based Skip List modified to provide logarithmic running time for insertion, removal, and random access lookup operations (e.g. get the element at the ith index).

    Invented by Bill Pugh in 1990, A Skip List is a probabilistic data structure for maintaining items in sorted order. Strictly speaking it is impossible to make any hard guarantees regarding the worst-case performance of this class. Practical performance is expected to be logarithmic with an extremely high degree of probability as the list grows.

    The following table summarizes the performance of this class compared to a TreeList (where n is the size of the list and m is the size of the specified collection):

    Method Running Time
    SkipList
    (expected)    		 TreeList
    (worst-case)
    addAll(Collection)
    containsAll(Collection)
    retainAll(Collection)
    removeAll(Collection)     		O(m log n)
    indexOf(Object)
    lastIndexOf(Object)
    get(int)
    remove(int)
    listIterator(int)     		O(log n) O(n)
    add(E)
    contains(Object)
    remove(Object)     		O(log n)
    clear()
    isEmpty()
    size()
    		 O(1)
    Iterator.remove()
    ListIterator.remove()     		O(log n) O(1)

    The subList view exhibits identical time complexity, with the exception of the clear() operation which runs in linear time proportional to the size of the view.

    Author:
    Zhenya Leonov

        Creates a new SkipList containing the elements of the specified Iterable. If the specified iterable is an instance of SortedSet, PriorityQueue, or SortedCollection, this list will be ordered according to the same ordering.       • listIterator

        public java.util.ListIterator<E> listIterator(int index)
        Returns a list iterator over the elements in this list (in proper sequence), starting at the specified position in the list. The specified index indicates the first element that would be returned by an initial call to next. An initial call to previous would return the element with the specified index minus one.

        This implementation returns a straightforward implementation of the ListIterator interface that extends the implementation of the Iterator interface returned by the iterator() method. The ListIterator implementation relies on the backing list's get(int), set(int, E), add(int, E) and remove(int) methods.

        Note that the list iterator returned by this implementation will throw an UnsupportedOperationException in response to its remove, set and add methods unless the list's remove(int), set(int, E), and add(int, E) methods are overridden.

        This implementation can be made to throw runtime exceptions in the face of concurrent modification, as described in the specification for the (protected) AbstractList.modCount field.

        The returned iterator does not support the add(E) and set(E) operations.

        Specified by:

        Description copied from class: java.util.AbstractCollection
        Removes a single instance of the specified element from this collection, if it is present (optional operation). More formally, removes an element e such that (o==null ? e==null : o.equals(e)), if this collection contains one or more such elements. Returns true if this collection contained the specified element (or equivalently, if this collection changed as a result of the call).
